The '''Protomap''' is a primordial molecular map of the functional areas of the mammalian [[cerebral cortex]] during early [[embryonic development]], at a stage when [[neural stem cells]] are still the dominant cell type.<ref name=":0" /> The protomap is a feature of the [[ventricular zone]], which contains the principal cortical progenitor cells, known as [[radial glial cell]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Noctor|first1=SC|last2=Flint|first2=AC|last3=Weissman|first3=TA|last4=Dammerman|first4=RS|last5=Kriegstein|first5=AR|title=Neurons derived from radial glial cells establish radial units in neocortex.|journal=Nature|date=8 February 2001|volume=409|issue=6821|pages=714–20|pmid=11217860|doi=10.1038/35055553}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rakic|first1=P|title=Evolution of the neocortex: a perspective from developmental biology.|journal=Nature Reviews. Neuroscience|date=October 2009|volume=10|issue=10|pages=724–35|pmid=19763105|doi=10.1038/nrn2719|pmc=2913577}}</ref> Through a process called '[[cortical patterning]]', the protomap is patterned by a system of signaling centers in the embryo, which provide positional information and cell fate instructions.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Grove|first1=EA|last2=Fukuchi-Shimogori|first2=T|title=Generating the cerebral cortical area map.|journal=Annual Review of Neuroscience|date=2003|volume=26|pages=355–80|pmid=14527269|doi=10.1146/annurev.neuro.26.041002.131137}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{cite journal|last1=Fukuchi-Shimogori|first1=T|last2=Grove|first2=EA|title=Neocortex patterning by the secreted signaling molecule FGF8.|journal=Science|date=2 November 2001|volume=294|issue=5544|pages=1071–4|pmid=11567107|doi=10.1126/science.1064252}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sur|first1=M|last2=Rubenstein|first2=JL|title=Patterning and plasticity of the cerebral cortex.|journal=Science|date=4 November 2005|volume=310|issue=5749|pages=805–10|pmid=16272112|doi=10.1126/science.1112070}}</ref> These early genetic instructions set in motion a development and maturation process that gives rise to the mature functional areas of the cortex, for example the visual, somatosensory, and motor areas. The term protomap was coined by [[Pasko Rakic]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|author=Rakic P |title=Specification of cerebral cortical areas |journal=Science |volume=241 |issue=4862 |pages=170–6 |date=July 1988 |pmid=3291116 |doi= 10.1126/science.3291116|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=3291116}}</ref> The ''protomap hypothesis'' was opposed by the ''protocortex hypothesis'', which proposes that cortical proto-areas initially have the same potential,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=O'Leary|first1=DD|title=Do cortical areas emerge from a protocortex?|journal=Trends in Neurosciences|date=October 1989|volume=12|issue=10|pages=400–6|pmid=2479138|doi=10.1016/0166-2236(89)90080-5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Cognitive Neuroscience of Development (Studies in Developmental Psychology) |publisher=Psychology Press |location=East Sussex |year=2003 |pages= |isbn=1-84169-214-X |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref> and that regionalization in large part is controlled by external influences, such as axonal inputs from the [[thalamus]] to the cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|vauthors=Sun T, Walsh CA |title=Molecular approaches to brain asymmetry and handedness |journal=Nature Reviews Neuroscience |volume=7 |issue= 8|pages=655–62 |date=August 2006 |doi=10.1038/nrn1930 |quote=[http://www.nature.com/nrn/journal/v7/n8/glossary/nrn1930.html Glossary] |pmid=16858393}}</ref> However, a series of papers in the year 2000 and in 2001 provided strong evidence against the protocortex hypothesis, and the protomap hypothesis has been well accepted since then.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bishop|first1=KM|last2=Goudreau|first2=G|last3=O'Leary|first3=DD|title=Regulation of area identity in the mammalian neocortex by Emx2 and Pax6.|journal=Science|date=14 April 2000|volume=288|issue=5464|pages=344–9|pmid=10764649|doi=10.1126/science.288.5464.344}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mallamaci|first1=A|last2=Muzio|first2=L|last3=Chan|first3=CH|last4=Parnavelas|first4=J|last5=Boncinelli|first5=E|title=Area identity shifts in the early cerebral cortex of Emx2-/- mutant mice.|journal=Nature Neuroscience|date=July 2000|volume=3|issue=7|pages=679–86|pmid=10862700|doi=10.1038/76630}}</ref> The protomap hypothesis, together with the related [[radial unit hypothesis]], forms our core understanding of the embryonic development of the cerebral cortex. Once the basic structure is present and cortical neurons have migrated to their final destinations, many other processes contribute to the maturation of functional cortical circuits.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ackman|first1=JB|last2=Burbridge|first2=TJ|last3=Crair|first3=MC|title=Retinal waves coordinate patterned activity throughout the developing visual system.|journal=Nature|date=11 October 2012|volume=490|issue=7419|pages=219–25|pmid=23060192|doi=10.1038/nature11529|pmc=3962269}}</ref>
